\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 50. J. biglumis} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 328 (1753). Plant usually caespitose, the rhizome with short internodes and producing leafy, non-flowering shoots and often long subterranean runners. Stems 2-20 cm, erect, with several basal leaves. Leaves short or occasionally up to 8 cm, 1- to 3-tubulose at base, unitubulose above; transverse septa usually present but not visible externally. Inflorescence with a single (1-)2(-4)-flowered head; flowers in a vertical row, the first bract erect, exceeding the flowers and often with a small lamina. Perianth-segments 2·5-3 mm, equal, elliptical to ovate or the inner slightly obovate, mostly dark brown to blackish. Stamens 6, usually slightly exceeding or equalling perianth. Anthers 0·3-0·4 mm, 1/8-1/6 as long as the filaments. Capsule 4-5 mm, 1½-2 times as long as the perianth, obtusely angled, emarginate, mucronate. Seeds 0·7-0·9 mm, with 2 subequal appendages 0·3-0·6 mm. 2n = 60.{\i  Wet places, mainly in the mountains; calcicole. N. Europe, southwards to }56° 15' {\i N. in Scotland; one station in C. Austria.} Au Br Fa Fe Is No Rs (N) Sb Su.
\par

